      {
        "award_id": "80NSSC23K0658",
        "generated_unique_award_id": "ASST_NON_80NSSC23K0658_080",
        "recipient_name": "University of Texas at Dallas",
        "recipient_id": "b31a6584-f8ff-0848-3b7a-04422c7b4762-C",
        "award_amount": 331604.0,
        "description": "Specifically  we will address the following three science objectives: (1) conduct statistics of Juno current sheet crossings over a wide range of radial distances and local times and determine the typical current sheet configurations and main mechanisms responsible for the stress balance (2) reveal the dependence of the current sheet configuration on the plasma content (relative contributions of different ion populations to the stress balance) and plasma characteristics (temperature  density  pressure anisotropy) (3) explore the role of accelerated field-aligned electron streams in the current sheet configuration and stress balance in the Jovian magnetodisk. To address these three objectives  we will use measurements from Juno S magnetic field instrument (MAG)  Jovian Auroral Distributions Experiment (JADE)  and Jupiter energetic-particle detector instrument (JEDI). We will also use Juno wave measurements (WAVES) to estimate the total plasma density. This project will use Juno measurements from the first 38 orbits  which include current sheet crossings at different radial distances over a wide range of local times.",
        "start_date": "2023-06-01",
        "end_date": "2026-05-31",
